# Tech Stack

- **Framework:** Next.js 16 (App Router) with React 19
- **Language:** TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Styling:** CSS Modules with native CSS nesting
- **Animation:** Motion (Framer Motion)
- **Linting/Formatting:** Biome
- **Backend services:** Firebase Admin
- **Images:** Cloudinary via `next/image`

# Server-First Components

Default to React Server Components. Only add `"use client"` when the component genuinely needs client-side hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useRef`, etc.) or browser APIs.

When a page needs interactivity, keep the page/layout as a server component and extract the interactive parts into small, focused client components.

```tsx
// page.tsx — server component (no "use client")
import { InteractiveWidget } from "./InteractiveWidget";

export default async function Page() {
  const data = await fetchData();
  return (
    <main>
      <h1>{data.title}</h1>
      <InteractiveWidget items={data.items} />
    </main>
  );
}
```

```tsx
// InteractiveWidget.tsx — client component (isolated)
"use client";
import { useState } from "react";

export function InteractiveWidget({ items }: { items: Item[] }) {
  const [active, setActive] = useState(0);
  return <div>...</div>;
}
```
